{"title_page": "Beverly Briley", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name             = Beverly Briley\n| image            = \n| order           = 1st [[Mayor of Nashville| Mayor of Metropolitan Nashville]]\n| vice mayor      = \n| predecessor     = \n| term_start         = 1963\n| term_end           = 1975\n| preceded=''Position established''\n| succeeded=[[Richard Fulton]]\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = January 11, 1914\n| birth_place      = Nashville, Tennessee, U.S.\n| death_date      = {{Death date and age|1980|9|14|1914|1|11}}\n| death_place     = Nashville, Tennessee, U.S.\n| constituency    =\n| party           = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| religion        = \n| profession      = \n| alma_mater     = [[Vanderbilt University]]<br/>[[Cumberland Law School]]\n| website         = \n}}\n'''Clifton Beverly Briley''' (January 11, 1914 &ndash; September 14, 1980) was an American attorney and politician, the first [[mayor]] of the newly consolidated [[metropolitan government]] of [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] and [[Davidson County, Tennessee|Davidson County]] in Tennessee.  Elected to the mayor's position in 1962 as a [[United States Democratic Party|Democrat]], Briley served three terms from 1963 to 1975; he was prevented by term limits from running again. He had previously served as county judge (chief executive) of Davidson County for several terms, from 1950 to 1963.\n\n==Early life==\nBriley was born in West Nashville, Tennessee in 1914.<ref name=Campbell>{{cite journal|title=Metro Mayor\u2014The Man and the Job|first=Chester D.|last=Campbell|journal=Nashville Magazine|volume=1|issue=1|date=January 1963}}</ref> Attending local schools, he became involved in [[Scouting in Tennessee|Scouting]] as a boy and attained the rank of [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]].<ref>https://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=248093</ref> He attended [[Vanderbilt University]] before transferring to the [[Cumberland Law School]], graduating in 1932. He was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1932.<ref>https://news.vanderbilt.edu/2015/09/16/vu-alumni-elected-to-metro-government-sept-10/</ref><ref>https://tennesseeencyclopedia.net/entries/beverly-briley/</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBriley began practicing in 1932.<ref name=\"tennesseanobit\">{{cite news|last1=Fontenay|first1=Charles L.|title=Ex-Metro Mayor Beverly Briley Dies Here at 66|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/112031414/?terms=%22Beverly%2BBriley%22|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=September 15, 1980|pages=1; 7|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Briley served in the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] during [[World War II]] as a quartermaster aboard the [[USS David W. Taylor (DD-551)|USS ''David Taylor'']].<ref name=Campbell/> After the war, he ran a successful campaign for county judge (chief executive) of Davidson County in 1950, serving until 1963.\n\nBriley was a champion of [[metropolitan government]] and supported the merger of Nashville and Davidson County government. In 1963 he won election against Davidson County tax assessor [[Clifford Allen]], another longtime Nashville [[politician]], and became the first mayor of what is known as Metro Nashville. In 1966, his main opponent was [[Ben West]], the former mayor of the earlier City of Nashville municipal government. Briley won the election in a [[Two-round system|runoff]]. Briley was reelected in 1971, also in a runoff. He was prevented by [[term limits]] from running again in 1975. He remained active in Nashville politics until his death five years later.  Altogether, he served as chief executive of Davidson County and of Nashville for 25 years.\n\nBriley took a fairly [[progressivism|progressive]] position on the [[Civil Rights Movement]], an important question for mayors of [[U.S. Southern states|Southern]] cities at the time. He readily cooperated with [[African American|black]] leaders and is generally credited with helping smooth the transition away from [[racial segregation]] in Nashville. Public schools and lunch counters had already been desegregated by the time he took office.<ref>https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/education/2017/09/08/desegregation-nashville-schools-and-bombing-followed-60-years-ago/637665001/</ref> In 1965, Briley described the [[Ku Klux Klan]] as \"merchants of hate\" and said they were \"not welcome\" in Nashville.<ref name=\"nashvilleway166\">{{cite book |last1=Houston |first1=Benjamin |title=The Nashville Way: Racial Etiquette and the Struggle for Social Justice in a Southern City |date=2012 |publisher=University of Georgia Press |location=Athens, Georgia |isbn=9780820343266|oclc=940632744 |page=166}}</ref>\n\nOn other issues, he was a [[American conservatism|conservative]] Democrat; in 1972 he was the area leader of \"[[Democrats for Nixon]],\" in an effort to strengthen southern support for Republican national candidates. That year, [[Richard Nixon|Nixon]] became the first Republican presidential candidate to carry Davidson County since the [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]] era. Most Republicans had been disenfranchised in Tennessee and other states when they passed new constitutions to suppress black voting by raising barriers to voter registration.\n\n==Personal life and death==\nBriley married Dorothy Gordon in 1934.<ref name=\"tennesseanobit\"/> They had two children together, Cliff and Diane.<ref name=Campbell/> He was an alcoholic.<ref name=\"tennesseanobit\"/> His grandson [[David Briley]] was the Mayor of Nashville after the resignation of [[Megan Barry]].\n\nBriley died of bladder cancer on September 14, 1980 at the [[Vanderbilt University Medical Center|Vanderbilt University Hospital]] in Nashville at the age of 66, just months after the death of his wife.<ref name=\"tennesseanobit\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/124539748/dorothy-christine-briley|title=Dorothy Christine Gordon Briley (1913-1980) -...|website=www.findagrave.com|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> His funeral was held at the Inglewood Baptist Church, and he was buried at [[Spring Hill Cemetery]] in Nashville.<ref name=\"tennesseanobit\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=The John Hilton Gordon Family, Rutherford County, Tennessee|first=Thomas Gilbert|last=Gordon|publisher=T.G. Gordon|date=1988}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy and honors==\n[[Briley Parkway]], a major [[beltway]] thoroughfare which runs by the [[Grand Ole Opry]] House and around much of the city, was named in his honor.\n\nThe city-owned Beverly Briley Building, a major component of Nashville's redesigned Public Square, was named for him.  \n\nHis grandson, [[Rob Briley]], was a politician who formerly represented the 52nd House District, a Nashville district, in the [[Tennessee General Assembly|state legislature]]. He also served as the Democratic Majority Floor Leader. Another grandson, [[David Briley]], served as mayor of Nashville.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nashville.gov/finance/Real_Property_Svc/real-property-courthouse-area.htm Public Square redesign details], City of Nashville\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Ben West]] | title = [[List of mayors of Nashville, Tennessee|Mayor of Nashville, Tennessee]] | years = 1963&mdash;1975 | after = [[Richard Fulton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Mayors of Nashville}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Briley, Beverly}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Heads of county government in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Democrats]]\n[[Category:Eagle Scouts]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Deaths from bladder cancer]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt University alumni]]\n[[Category:Cumberland School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Tennessee lawyers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name             = Beverly Briley\n| image            = \n| order           = 1st [[Mayor of Nashville| Mayor of Metropolitan Nashville]]\n| vice mayor      = \n| predecessor     = \n| term_start         = 1963\n| term_end           = 1975\n| preceded=Position Established\n| succeeded=[[Richard Fulton]]\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = January 11, 1914\n| birth_place      = Nashville, Tennessee, U.S.\n| death_date      = {{Death date and age|1980|9|14|1914|1|11}}\n| death_place     = Nashville, Tennessee, U.S.\n| constituency    =\n| party           = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| religion        = \n| profession      = \n| alma_mater     = [[Vanderbilt University]]<br/>[[Cumberland Law School]]\n| website         = \n}}\n'''Clifton Beverly Briley''' (January 11, 1914 &ndash; September 14, 1980) was an American attorney and politician, the first [[mayor]] of the newly consolidated [[metropolitan government]] of [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] and [[Davidson County, Tennessee|Davidson County]] in Tennessee.  Elected to the mayor's position in 1962 as a [[United States Democratic Party|Democrat]], Briley served three terms from 1963 to 1975; he was prevented by term limits from running again. He had previously served as county judge (chief executive) of Davidson County for several terms, from 1950 to 1963.\n\n==Early life==\nBriley was born in West Nashville, Tennessee in 1914.<ref name=Campbell>{{cite journal|title=Metro Mayor\u2014The Man and the Job|first=Chester D.|last=Campbell|journal=Nashville Magazine|volume=1|issue=1|date=January 1963}}</ref> Attending local schools, he became involved in [[Scouting in Tennessee|Scouting]] as a boy and attained the rank of [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]].<ref>https://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=248093</ref> He attended [[Vanderbilt University]] before transferring to the [[Cumberland Law School]], graduating in 1932. He was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1932.<ref>https://news.vanderbilt.edu/2015/09/16/vu-alumni-elected-to-metro-government-sept-10/</ref><ref>https://tennesseeencyclopedia.net/entries/beverly-briley/</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBriley began practicing in 1932.<ref name=\"tennesseanobit\">{{cite news|last1=Fontenay|first1=Charles L.|title=Ex-Metro Mayor Beverly Briley Dies Here at 66|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/112031414/?terms=%22Beverly%2BBriley%22|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=September 15, 1980|pages=1; 7|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Briley served in the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] during [[World War II]] as a quartermaster aboard the [[USS David W. Taylor (DD-551)|USS ''David Taylor'']].<ref name=Campbell/> After the war, he ran a successful campaign for county judge (chief executive) of Davidson County in 1950, serving until 1963.\n\nBriley was a champion of [[metropolitan government]] and supported the merger of Nashville and Davidson County government. In 1963 he won election against Davidson County tax assessor [[Clifford Allen]], another longtime Nashville [[politician]], and became the first mayor of what is known as Metro Nashville. In 1966, his main opponent was [[Ben West]], the former mayor of the earlier City of Nashville municipal government. Briley won the election in a [[Two-round system|runoff]]. Briley was reelected in 1971, also in a runoff. He was prevented by [[term limits]] from running again in 1975. He remained active in Nashville politics until his death five years later.  Altogether, he served as chief executive of Davidson County and of Nashville for 25 years.\n\nBriley took a fairly [[progressivism|progressive]] position on the [[Civil Rights Movement]], an important question for mayors of [[U.S. Southern states|Southern]] cities at the time. He readily cooperated with [[African American|black]] leaders and is generally credited with helping smooth the transition away from [[racial segregation]] in Nashville. Public schools and lunch counters had already been desegregated by the time he took office.<ref>https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/education/2017/09/08/desegregation-nashville-schools-and-bombing-followed-60-years-ago/637665001/</ref> In 1965, Briley described the [[Ku Klux Klan]] as \"merchants of hate\" and said they were \"not welcome\" in Nashville.<ref name=\"nashvilleway166\">{{cite book |last1=Houston |first1=Benjamin |title=The Nashville Way: Racial Etiquette and the Struggle for Social Justice in a Southern City |date=2012 |publisher=University of Georgia Press |location=Athens, Georgia |isbn=9780820343266|oclc=940632744 |page=166}}</ref>\n\nOn other issues, he was a [[American conservatism|conservative]] Democrat; in 1972 he was the area leader of \"[[Democrats for Nixon]],\" in an effort to strengthen southern support for Republican national candidates. That year, [[Richard Nixon|Nixon]] became the first Republican presidential candidate to carry Davidson County since the [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]] era. Most Republicans had been disenfranchised in Tennessee and other states when they passed new constitutions to suppress black voting by raising barriers to voter registration.\n\n==Personal life and death==\nBriley married Dorothy Gordon in 1934.<ref name=\"tennesseanobit\"/> They had two children together, Cliff and Diane.<ref name=Campbell/> He was an alcoholic.<ref name=\"tennesseanobit\"/> His grandson [[David Briley]] was the Mayor of Nashville after the resignation of [[Megan Barry]].\n\nBriley died of bladder cancer on September 14, 1980 at the [[Vanderbilt University Medical Center|Vanderbilt University Hospital]] in Nashville at the age of 66, just months after the death of his wife.<ref name=\"tennesseanobit\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/124539748/dorothy-christine-briley|title=Dorothy Christine Gordon Briley (1913-1980) -...|website=www.findagrave.com|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> His funeral was held at the Inglewood Baptist Church, and he was buried at [[Spring Hill Cemetery]] in Nashville.<ref name=\"tennesseanobit\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=The John Hilton Gordon Family, Rutherford County, Tennessee|first=Thomas Gilbert|last=Gordon|publisher=T.G. Gordon|date=1988}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy and honors==\n[[Briley Parkway]], a major [[beltway]] thoroughfare which runs by the [[Grand Ole Opry]] House and around much of the city, was named in his honor.\n\nThe city-owned Beverly Briley Building, a major component of Nashville's redesigned Public Square, was named for him.  \n\nHis grandson, [[Rob Briley]], was a politician who formerly represented the 52nd House District, a Nashville district, in the [[Tennessee General Assembly|state legislature]]. He also served as the Democratic Majority Floor Leader. Another grandson, [[David Briley]], served as mayor of Nashville.{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nashville.gov/finance/Real_Property_Svc/real-property-courthouse-area.htm Public Square redesign details], City of Nashville\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Ben West]] | title = [[List of mayors of Nashville, Tennessee|Mayor of Nashville, Tennessee]] | years = 1963&mdash;1975 | after = [[Richard Fulton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Mayors of Nashville}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Briley, Beverly}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Heads of county government in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Democrats]]\n[[Category:Eagle Scouts]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Deaths from bladder cancer]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt University alumni]]\n[[Category:C